##With more than 10,000 new coronavirus infections abroad, why hasn't World Health Organization declared a "pandemic" ?

Micro Signal deeptechchina

Function description DeepTech is a full-chain content, service, data and investment and financing platform focusing on the emerging technology industrialization, and is committed to building a global network of scientific and technological innovation cooperation.

With the rapid spread of the new coronavirus around the world, the trend of a global pandemic seems inevitable. But there are still polarizing views on whether to declare a global pandemic.

GENEVA, March 3, the World Health Organization released its latest daily report on the development of COVID-19. As of 10:00 a.m. Central European time on March 3, a total of 10,566 cases of new pneumonia and 166 deaths had been confirmed in 72 countries outside China (compared with 64 the previous day) . Compared with the previous day's report, 1,792 new cases and 38 new deaths have been confirmed outside China.

WHO Director General Tan Desai said at a regular briefing that the number of new cases of cap in China had continued to decline, with 119 new cases reported in the past 24 hours, the lowest number since January 20. The number of new cases outside China is already 15 times that of new cases inside China. South Korea, Italy, Iran and Japan are four of the most worrying countries, with 80 per cent of confirmed cases outside the country coming from South Korea, Iran and Italy.

Fig. | Map of new coronavirus outbreak (Source: Who)

At the time of writing, World Health Organization's website counted 91,783 confirmed cases and 3,123 deaths worldwide. As can be seen from the above-mentioned map, the current outbreak of countries have been spread over five continents, only Antarctica survived.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
###A once-in-a-century "pandemic" ?

As more data become available to WHO, the virus and the diseases it causes are increasingly known. The new coronavirus was neither SARS, nor Mers, nor influenza, Tandser said; it was a novel virus with unique characteristics. Both coronaviruses and influenza cause respiratory disease and spread through similar channels. However, there are several important differences between new crown outbreaks and influenza.

First, based on current data, the COVID-19 is not spreading as efficiently as the flu. That's because influenza is spread mostly from people who are infected but not yet sick, and the new coronavirus doesn't seem to be. According to current data, only 1% of reported cases are "asymptomatic, " and most cases develop symptoms within 2 days. Note, however, that the disease caused by the new coronavirus is more serious than that caused by seasonal influenza because it is a new virus and no one is immune to it, and many people around the world have developed immunity to seasonal influenza strains.

Also, people have vaccines and treatments for seasonal flu. But for the new coronavirus, there is no vaccine, there is no specific treatment for the virus, so people should be vigilant. Clinical trials of therapeutic drugs are under way in many countries, and more than 20 vaccines are under development. Finally, WHO has never discussed the control of seasonal influenza, because that is not possible. But for the new coronavirus, it is possible to contain its spread. Therefore, countries should target contact tracing for the new coronavirus, which can prevent infection and save lives.

WHO Director General Tan Desai, whose birthday is also on March 3, said at a press conference that he had received a gift from Congo, Africa -- a gift of Ebola -- for two weeks without a reported case, and that no patients were currently receiving treatment; But he also said that "another war is getting more complicated" (Source: Twitter / WHO) 

As new cases of coronaviruses are confirmed in Asia, the Middle East and Europe, there is growing concern that the epidemic is spreading into a new "pandemic" that is spreading around the world. In the United States, there have been just over 100 confirmed cases of new pneumonia and nine deaths. But Dr. Scott Gottlieb, a former head of the food and Drug Administration, told reporters there could be "hundreds or thousands" of undiagnosed cases of new pneumonia in the United States, at least two, if not four, states are experiencing "community transmission" .

The Bill Gates said on February 28th that the new coronavirus might be a once-in-a-century "pandemic" ; but World Health Organization apparently is more cautious about using "pandemic" to define COVID-19. Who director-general Tan Desai announced at a regular media briefing on February 28 that the World Health Organization (WHO) had raised the global risk level for a new pneumonia outbreak from "high risk" to "very high" , but had not decided to use "pandemic" to describe the epidemic.

Perhaps the problem is that the declaration of a "pandemic" comes at a time when many countries have taken measures to control the development of the epidemic and protect public health and safety, on the one hand, it will help launch more emergency action plans around the world, but on the other hand, it will probably cause more damage to people's daily lives.

(Source: Twitter / WHO)

###What is a "pandemic" ?

The very idea of a "pandemic" is enough to cause alarm, even panic. This is partly due to the fact that different English words describe different levels of development of the epidemic. Typically, an outbreak is described in three English words: outbreak, epidemic, and pandemic. In the early stages of a disease outbreak, "outbreak" is used to indicate a "sudden increase in the number of cases. " The impact could extend from a single community to several countries, but on a much smaller scale than the epidemic.

An infectious disease is called an epidemic when it spreads rapidly to a large number of people. And if the disease is not contained and continues to spread, public health officials may consider calling it a pandemic, meaning that the epidemic has affected enough people in different parts of the world, to the point of global outbreak. It also means that the number of people infected, the number of deaths, and the social and economic impact will be most widespread when the epidemic is called pandemic.

Yan Zhong Huang, senior research fellow for Global Health at the Council on Foreign Relations, told DeepTech that the definition of a pandemic is actually pretty vague, and that a sustained, large scale, worldwide epidemic is a pandemic. "It operates with a degree of flexibility. "

Historically, the Spanish flu of 1918-1919 was a pandemic, killing between 20 and 40 million people worldwide. The closest we have come is the 2009 influenza a (H1N1) pandemic, the first "PHEIC" public health emergency of international concern since the implementation of the international health regulations in 2005.

As of mid March 2010, the then H1N1 flu epidemic had sickened 59 million Americans, hospitalized 265,000 and killed 12,000, according to U.S. CDC estimates. In addition, 186 countries (and territories) have confirmed cases of influenza a (H1N1) globally and 72 countries (and territories) have reported deaths (data updated in January 2020) .

Figure | map of affected countries and deaths as of 31 July 2009(Source: Who)

Back to the outbreak, there are now more than 90,000 confirmed cases worldwide, in nearly 80 countries, far short of the scale of the 2009 H1N1 pandemic. But according to the 2010"technical criteria" for a pandemic on the WHO website, a new viral infection that most people are not immune to has emerged and spread around the world, according to media reports. While pandemics may look similar in some respects to regular flu, they may have other entirely different characteristics, such as the fact that both seasonal and pandemic influenza can cause infections throughout the age range, in most cases, it leads to self-limited disease, in which the patient recovers completely without treatment. However, the proportion of severe cases in a "pandemic" is likely to be higher and not seasonal in duration, and outbreaks may occur even in the summer.

In fact, the 2010 promulgation of the "Technical Standards" and the 2009 World Health Organization declared a (H1N1) influenza a pandemic is closely linked. After who declared influenza a a a a pandemic, which led to a short period of concentrated resources in vaccine development, the disease later proved to have limited impact, this has led many to criticise the WHO's response as "excessive" .

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
"In 2009, it was kind of a joke to block a virus that had a lower mortality rate than the flu, " Huang said, adding that the announcement of a pandemic had rattled people and consumed a lot of resources. In Asian countries in particular, a lot of resources were devoted to containment policies that turned out to be largely unnecessary.

Dr. Margaret Chan, who's director general at the time, later wrote a letter to the British Medical Journal explaining the "technical criteria" for "why H1N1 was declared a pandemic in the first place and what the indicators were. ".

That may also be one reason why the WHO has been unusually cautious in determining whether the outbreak has been declared a "pandemic" .

###The impact of the pandemic

WHO Director General Tan Desai stressed on February 24 that the new pneumonia outbreak can not yet be described as a pandemic. There was no "runaway global spread" or "massive and severe disease or death" . But then, on February 28th, World Health Organization announced that it had raised the global risk of a new pneumonia outbreak from "high risk" to "very high" .

We should be prepared for the possibility of a global epidemic, Tandser said. But the key question is not what word to use to describe an outbreak. Using "pandemic" or not does not interfere with any single infection or help save anyone's life. It is time for all nations, communities, families and individuals to focus on getting ready to contain the epidemic.

We do not live in a black-and-white world, and pandemics or pandemics are not a Either/Or problem. At the same time, some aspects of the source and spread of COVID-19 have yet to be investigated. These factors make it difficult to declare a pandemic, especially as there are early signs of a slowdown in countries such as China, Singapore and Vietnam. Furthermore, declaring an infectious disease a pandemic would neither provide who with additional support and assistance nor would it be given new powers.

Moreover, "public health emergencies of international concern (PHEIC) " has been the WHO's highest alert level on the epidemic, there is no "pandemic" to indicate the extent of the impact of clear regulations. As a specialized agency of the United Nations and the largest Intergovernmental Health Organization, who has no authority over how countries or regions should operate in the face of an epidemic and can only make calls and recommendations, but declaring an outbreak a pandemic is likely to spur more countries to roll out higher-level emergency responses at the local or state level.

The U.S. CDC, for example, has a range of measures for pandemics, including closing schools, telecommuting, and canceling more public events. And if taken on a large scale, these measures are likely to cause more panic and loss to the public than the virus. When the number of new cases of pneumonia in the United States rose to 69 and there were three cases of "unknown origin" infection, US media reported, supermarkets across the United States have seen people lining up to buy food, oil, Rice, paper, water and other supplies, and some have begun stockpiling bullets for fear that the situation will get out of hand.

(Source: MIT Technology Review)

Before the new coronavirus reached such a global scale, World Health Organization in mid-january called the panic and confusion caused by the new coronavirus an "information epidemic. " "there is a lot of mixed news on social media about the outbreak, " he said, adding to the public's fear of the outbreak. At the same time, the rapid spread of false information through social media has triggered a crisis of public trust and fuelled panic and racism both inside and outside the network.

Avoiding further aggravation of the population's panic and reducing the risk of possible violence may also be a key consideration for who.

Today, the world economy is so interconnected that when one country suffers, others suffer. The impact is even greater, especially for a major engine of the world economy like China. Ebola in West Africa, for example, will have an impact on the rest of the world, but not in the same way.

In Huang's view, globalisation could be the biggest casualty of a declared "pandemic" , as China has embraced globalisation and championed its free trade. If this outbreak hits the world economy hard, more countries may be less confident about free trade and globalisation.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
###Additional: Update on outbreaks in other countries

Whether or not a "pandemic" is declared, countries and regions should be prepared to take appropriate preventive measures. There is no one size fits all approach and each country must conduct its own risk assessment based on its own circumstances, Tandsey said. Who is also continuing its own risk assessment and monitoring the evolution of the epidemic day and night. "We have to focus on prevention and control while doing everything we can to prepare for the potential for the long-term viability of the virus. "

The response to contain the outbreak has also varied from country to country, with seemingly "Buddhist" Singapore once having the second highest number of infections after China, but as of February 29, singapore confirmed a total of 102 cases of new pneumonia, no deaths. Since 21 February, the number of cured cases has exceeded the number of new cases; on 23 February, zero new cases were recorded. This is due to the rapid response of its government and the existence of a well-developed and Proven Disease Response System; in addition, the impact of epidemic prevention on daily life and advice to the population are clearly spelled out. This has given the local population an insight into the severity of the new coronavirus. To a certain extent, can reduce the unnecessary panic.

As Japan, which worries the World Health Organization, speaking before the Senate Budget Committee on the morning of March 2, Japanese Prime Minister Shinz Abe said: "In order to prevent all possible scenarios and minimize the impact of the epidemic on national life, the government should move forward as soon as possible with the legislative process to develop measures equivalent to the new influenza special measures law, including the implementation of regulations declaring a state of emergency. " He also stressed that, according to experts, the next 1-2 weeks will be a critical time to decide whether the new pneumonia epidemic in Japan will expand rapidly or gradually ease.

A few days earlier, on Feb. 27, Anbe had ordered schools across Japan to suspend classes to prevent the massive spread of the new coronavirus. March 2 was the first day of the national primary, primary and high school suspensions. But even with five days to schedule from the announcement to the suspension, leaving time for local preparation and a "window" for the spread of the virus, but on March 2, some local governments refused to suspend classes, either "without any reason" or "because of the heavy burden on parents and businesses" . It remains to be seen how Japan's epidemic will develop in the future, given that Singapore is the front runner for a "normal flu" response.

Some Tokyo supermarkets no longer have ramen noodles on their shelves (Twitter) 

According to a Feb. 25 survey, Nishipo, a professor at the Hokkaido University School of Medicine and a member of the government's expert meeting, estimated that more than 940 people would be infected in Hokkaido. "The number of reported cases in Hokkaido is 77, but the estimate is 10 times that figure, " he said. "The idea that people with mild illness do not spread to young people is not a reasonable assumption. "

Another neighbor, South Korea, reported 5,328 new cases of pneumonia and 32 deaths in South Korea on March 3, with 516 new cases confirmed that day, Yonhap reported. President Moon jae-in told a weekly cabinet meeting on the morning of March 3 that South Korea had declared a "war" on the new coronavirus as the crisis in Taegu and nearby North Gyeongsang Province reached its peak, all government agencies are on 24-hour alert and plan to directly or indirectly inject 30 trillion won (170 billion yuan) into the new coronavirus response.

In Europe, the European Centre for Disease Control and Prevention raised the COVID-19 risk level from "moderate" to "high" as a new outbreak of pneumonia spread. The number of confirmed cases in Italy has risen sharply, from 2,036 to 2,502, with 79 deaths, overtaking Iran as the country with the highest number of deaths outside China, overseas media reported. At present, Italy has a number of outbreaks in the town to take closed measures.

The number of confirmed cases of the new coronavirus in Spain has climbed to 150, with seven patients in intensive care and 13 involving health workers, according to data updated on March 3. In addition, Spain has confirmed the first case of death from the new coronavirus, a man who died on 13 February after an autopsy revealed that the cause of death was a new coronavirus outbreak. The French government closed the Louvre Museum in Paris on March 1, with no clear opening date. Germany has also announced the cancellation of large-scale events such as exhibitions and sports events, while German Interior Minister Horst Seehofer Lorenz told the media that he would not rule out closing some areas or cities in response to the outbreak.

Image | supermarkets in the AFFORI region of Milan, Italy, are known online as "people's mass hysteria" (Twitter) 

In the UK, 12 new cases were confirmed on March 3, bringing the total number of cases to 51. Matt Hancock, the health and social work secretary, told the BBC there would be an emergency "battle plan" if the virus spread further, they include considering measures such as banning large gatherings, Stopping Football Games, closing schools and advising people to use public transport less, as long as they are "epidemiologically and scientifically sound" . But Matt also stressed that the measures are only under consideration and no decision has yet been made. People do not have to choose to close schools or other institutions until Public Health UK releases its official recommendations. And if the new pneumonia spreads further in the UK, the government will plan to recall retired doctors and nurses to work in the healthcare system and advise people to work from home."

In Iran, where the Middle East has been most affected, media reported 2,300 new cases of pneumonia and 77 cumulative deaths. There are currently more than 4,300 suspected cases. Iran's Health Ministry said it would translate China's treatment plan into Persian and carry out nationwide house-to-house inspections.

Back in China, after the outbreak was detected and strict control measures were taken, the epidemic has now been brought under control thanks to the unremitting efforts of the whole country's people and medical workers. However, according to the Guangdong Health Commission released the news on the evening of March 1, Shenzhen Health Commission reported a confirmed case of imported new crown pneumonia from the United Kingdom. Beijing has also had two imported confirmed cases with symptoms in Iran. In Zhejiang, there were 8 new imported Italian confirmed cases in two days of March 1 and 2.

Therefore, at present, while continuing to do a good job in the prevention and control of domestic epidemics, we should also raise our vigilance against imported cases from abroad, and carry out more stringent health testing in the entry and exit management, in order to avoid the epidemic infection number has the possibility of a "resurgence" . At present, Beijing, Shanghai and other places have already put in place relevant measures. One of the core contents is the 14-day isolation. No distinction is made between domestic and foreign countries, there will be no discrimination, there will be no exceptions, only non-discrimination and strict enforcement.
